WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:12.541 --> 00:00:14.194
How did you discover your passion
你如何发现自己的兴趣点

2
00:00:14.218 --> 00:00:15.747
or find your career?
或者找到喜欢的职业？

3
00:00:15.771 --> 00:00:17.187
Were you exposed to it?
是它们自己找上门来？

4
00:00:17.211 --> 00:00:18.822
Or was it trial and error?
还是你不断地主动尝试寻找？

5
00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:22.369
As child rights advocate Marian Wright Edelman said,
正如儿童权益拥护者 Marian Wright Edelman 所说：

6
00:00:22.393 --> 00:00:24.897
"You can't be what you can't see."
“你无法变成一个你不了解样子。”

7
00:00:25.393 --> 00:00:27.608
Fortunately, we now live in a time
幸运的是，我们生活在

8
00:00:27.632 --> 00:00:31.347
when emerging technologies may help us to solve this problem.
一个新兴技术可以帮我们 解决此问题的时代。

9
00:00:31.843 --> 00:00:33.206
For the past two years,
在过去的两年里，

10
00:00:33.230 --> 00:00:35.977
I've been developing an extended reality program
我在开发一个扩展现实项目。

11
00:00:36.001 --> 00:00:39.383
that enables middle school students from across the country
它让全国的中学生

12
00:00:39.407 --> 00:00:42.005
to take on the role of a marine biologist --
能够扮演海洋生物学家，

13
00:00:42.029 --> 00:00:44.307
even if they've never seen the ocean.
哪怕它们从来没有见过大海。

14
00:00:45.274 --> 00:00:48.663
As one seventh grader who recently completed our program said,
正如一个七年级的学生 最近完成了我们的项目后说：

15
00:00:48.687 --> 00:00:50.792
"I could see myself as a scientist,
“我可以把自己看作一个科学家，

16
00:00:50.816 --> 00:00:52.763
because I enjoyed this game."
因为我喜欢这个游戏。”

17
00:00:53.658 --> 00:00:55.622
This feedback really excited me,
这一反馈让我十分的激动，

18
00:00:55.646 --> 00:00:59.075
because too few students do see themselves as scientists.
因为很少有学生真的 把他们自己视作科学家。

19
00:00:59.669 --> 00:01:05.428
A 2014 study showed that 57 percent of eighth- and ninth-grade students
一个 2014 年的研究表明， 57% 的八年级和九年级学生认为

20
00:01:05.452 --> 00:01:07.286
said, "Science isn't me."
“科学不适合我。”

21
00:01:07.938 --> 00:01:10.380
Coincidentally, also in 2014,
很巧的是，也是在 2014 年，

22
00:01:10.404 --> 00:01:13.355
I met Mandë Holford, a marine biochemist,
我遇见了一位海洋生物学家， Mandë Holford；

23
00:01:13.379 --> 00:01:16.177
and Lindsay Portnoy, an educational psychologist.
还有一位教育心理学家， Lindsay Portnoy。

24
00:01:16.560 --> 00:01:18.458
The three of us shared a passion
我们三个有一个共同的爱好，

25
00:01:18.482 --> 00:01:22.621
for getting students excited by and comfortable with science.
就是让学生们适应并且爱上科学。

26
00:01:23.079 --> 00:01:25.308
We thought about how we could give children
我们思考如何能给孩子们带来

27
00:01:25.332 --> 00:01:28.241
the most realistic experience of a scientific career.
一个最真实的科学职业体验。

28
00:01:28.645 --> 00:01:29.980
We discussed the research;
我们讨论了这个研究，

29
00:01:30.004 --> 00:01:34.816
it showed that students felt comfortable taking risks when playing games.
它表明学生能够 在玩游戏时很自然地冒险。

30
00:01:34.840 --> 00:01:38.413
So the three of us started an educational games company
所以我们三个成立了 一个教育性质的游戏公司，

31
00:01:38.437 --> 00:01:40.228
to bring science to life.
赋予科学以生命。

32
00:01:41.190 --> 00:01:45.578
Virtual reality seemed like a low-cost way of increasing access.
虚拟现实看起来是个 低成本的扩大受众群体的方式。

33
00:01:45.602 --> 00:01:48.246
In addition, academic research has shown
此外，有学术研究表明，

34
00:01:48.270 --> 00:01:51.886
that virtual reality may lead to increases in learning retention.
虚拟现实或许能增强学习的记忆力。

35
00:01:52.188 --> 00:01:54.975
This was perfect for us, as we wanted to be in schools
这对我们来说再好不过了， 因为我们想在学校里实施，

36
00:01:54.999 --> 00:01:57.835
so that we could reach the most number of students possible,
这样我们就可以接触到 尽可能多的学生，

37
00:01:57.859 --> 00:02:00.990
particularly students who have been underrepresented in science.
尤其是那些很少接触科学的学生。

38
00:02:01.442 --> 00:02:04.503
So, with funding from the National Science Foundation,
在获得了国家科学基金会的支持后，

39
00:02:04.527 --> 00:02:07.234
we began developing our extended reality program
我们开始创办扩展现实项目，

40
00:02:07.258 --> 00:02:09.123
that combined virtual reality
它结合了虚拟现实（VR）

41
00:02:09.147 --> 00:02:11.363
with personalized digital journaling.
和个性化数字日志。

42
00:02:11.855 --> 00:02:13.902
We worked with teachers while developing it
我们在研发过程中 和教师们一起工作，

43
00:02:13.926 --> 00:02:17.926
to ensure that it would fit seamlessly into existing curricula
这样可以保证该项目能和 现有课程的无缝对接，

44
00:02:17.950 --> 00:02:21.975
and empower teachers to use cutting-edge technology in their classroom.
并且老师们能够 在课堂上使用先进的技术。

45
00:02:22.506 --> 00:02:25.061
We designed the virtual reality for Google Cardboard,
我们为 Google Cardboard  设计了虚拟现实体验，

46
00:02:25.085 --> 00:02:27.097
which requires only a smartphone
只需要一部智能手机

47
00:02:27.121 --> 00:02:31.260
and a 10 dollar VR viewer  made of cardboard.
和一个成本只有 10 美元， 用硬纸板制成的 VR 查看器。

48
00:02:31.653 --> 00:02:33.564
With this inexpensive headset,
有了这个便宜的装置，

49
00:02:33.588 --> 00:02:36.607
students are transported to an underwater expedition.
学生们参与了一次水下考察。

50
00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:38.949
Students use their digital journal
学生们用电子日志

51
00:02:38.973 --> 00:02:40.801
to write down their notes,
记笔记，

52
00:02:40.825 --> 00:02:42.211
to answer questions,
回答问题 ，

53
00:02:42.235 --> 00:02:43.552
to construct models
构建模型，

54
00:02:43.576 --> 00:02:45.095
and to develop hypotheses.
并提出假说。

55
00:02:45.512 --> 00:02:48.785
Students then go to the virtual world to test their hypotheses
之后，学生们进入 虚拟世界来验证他们的假说，

56
00:02:48.809 --> 00:02:50.275
and see if they're accurate,
看它们是否正确，

57
00:02:50.299 --> 00:02:52.449
much as scientists go to the field
就像科学家们在他们的工作中

58
00:02:52.473 --> 00:02:54.143
in their careers.
去实地考察一样。

59
00:02:54.874 --> 00:02:57.035
When students return to their digital journal,
当学生们回到了电子日志，

60
00:02:57.059 --> 00:02:59.393
they share their observations, claims,
他们会分享自己的观察，主张，

61
00:02:59.417 --> 00:03:01.213
reasoning and evidence.
推理还有证据。

62
00:03:01.745 --> 00:03:05.906
The students' written answers and virtual interactions
学生们写下的答案还有虚拟的互动

63
00:03:05.930 --> 00:03:07.684
are all updated live
都会在一个

64
00:03:07.708 --> 00:03:09.685
in an educator assessment dashboard,
教育评估操作界面被实时更新，

65
00:03:09.709 --> 00:03:12.222
so that teachers can follow their progress
这样老师们就可以监督他们的进度，

66
00:03:12.246 --> 00:03:14.857
and support them as needed.
并在他们需要的时候给予帮助。

67
00:03:14.881 --> 00:03:17.187
To give you a better sense, I'm going to show you
为了使你们有一个更直观的感受， 我下面要向大家展示

68
00:03:17.211 --> 00:03:18.951
a little bit of what students see.
学生们看到的一些东西。

69
00:03:19.959 --> 00:03:22.469
This is the virtual reality when they're underwater
这个虚拟现实片段的内容是， 他们正在水下

70
00:03:22.493 --> 00:03:24.871
observing the flora and fauna.
观察动植物群。

71
00:03:26.435 --> 00:03:29.603
This is the digital journal where they're constructing their models
利用这个电子日志， 他们能根据这些非生物数据

72
00:03:28.933 --> 00:03:32.494
based on this abiotic data to show what they expect to see.
建立模型，来展示 他们希望看到的东西。

73
00:03:33.525 --> 00:03:36.255
Here, they're supporting that with qualitative statements.
这里，他们正用定性的陈述 来支持他们的模型。

74
00:03:36.279 --> 00:03:39.024
And this is the educator dashboard that shows progress
这个是教育操作界面， 能够显示学生的进度，

75
00:03:39.048 --> 00:03:42.449
and enables [teachers] to see the students' answers as they go.
并且让老师们看到 进展过程中学生们的答案。

76
00:03:44.587 --> 00:03:46.618
When we were creating BioDive,
需要强调的是， 当我们设计 BioDive 时，

77
00:03:46.642 --> 00:03:48.806
again, we really wanted to focus on access,
我们想聚焦在访问性上，

78
00:03:48.830 --> 00:03:52.834
so we designed it to require only one phone for every four students.
所以在设计时，让它支持 每四名学生只能用一部手机。

79
00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:56.779
We also knew how collaborative science work is,
我们也知道科学工作多么需要合作，

80
00:03:56.803 --> 00:03:59.667
so we constructed the experience to only be solved
所以我们设计的这些体验

81
00:03:59.691 --> 00:04:01.196
through collaborative teamwork,
只能通过合作完成，

82
00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:04.819
as each student is an expert in a different geographic location.
每个学生在不同的地理位置是名专家。

83
00:04:05.864 --> 00:04:08.877
Given that these children's brains are still developing,
鉴于这些孩子们的大脑仍在发育，

84
00:04:08.901 --> 00:04:13.039
we limited each experience to last a maximum of two minutes.
我们将每次体验的时长 限制在两分钟内。

85
00:04:13.063 --> 00:04:17.210
And finally, because we know the importance of repeated exposure
最后，我们知道反复温习

86
00:04:17.234 --> 00:04:18.906
for internalizing knowledge,
对于内化知识十分重要，

87
00:04:18.930 --> 00:04:22.579
we constructed BioDive to take place over five class periods.
于是设计让 BioDive  延续超过五个课时。

88
00:04:23.462 --> 00:04:26.986
We started piloting BioDive in 2017
我们于 2017 年开始在纽约和新泽西

89
00:04:27.010 --> 00:04:29.625
in 20 schools in New York and New Jersey.
的 20 所学校试验 BioDive。

90
00:04:29.649 --> 00:04:33.012
We wanted to see students as they were using this new technology.
我们想观察学生们使用这项新技术。

91
00:04:33.647 --> 00:04:35.843
In 2019, now,
在 2019，也就是现在，

92
00:04:35.867 --> 00:04:39.273
we are now piloting in 26 states.
我们已经在 26 个州进行试用。

93
00:04:39.815 --> 00:04:42.692
What we have heard from teachers who have taught our program:
我们听教过这个项目的老师们说：

94
00:04:42.716 --> 00:04:46.749
"It was a nice way to show ocean dynamics without the luxury of actually being there
“鉴于我们在俄亥俄州，这是一种 不需要花大价钱就能向学生展示

95
00:04:46.773 --> 00:04:47.948
since we are in Ohio."
海洋动力学的方式。”

96
00:04:47.972 --> 00:04:49.047
(Laughter)
（笑声)

97
00:04:49.071 --> 00:04:50.397
"It's pretty mind-blowing."
“这十分令人兴奋。”

98
00:04:50.421 --> 00:04:52.557
"The students were totally engaged."
“学生们完全参与了进来。”

99
00:04:53.090 --> 00:04:56.560
But what really gives us hope is what we're hearing from students.
但是真正给了我们希望的 是我们从学生那儿听到的话。

100
00:04:57.029 --> 00:04:58.919
"I liked how it felt like I was there."
“我喜欢那种身临其境的感觉。”

101
00:04:58.943 --> 00:05:01.420
"It's interactive and a fun way to learn."
“这是一种互动性 且有趣的学习方式。”

102
00:05:01.444 --> 00:05:05.398
"It really gave me realistic examples of how these organisms appear."
“这给了我一个实例， 让我知道这些生物长什么样子。”

103
00:05:05.922 --> 00:05:10.240
"I could see myself as a scientist because it seems really fun."
“我感觉自己就像科学家， 因为这看起来很有趣。”

104
00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:13.335
Our feedback wasn't always so positive.
不过我们得到的反馈不总是好的。

105
00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:15.338
When we began developing,
我们刚开始研发时，

106
00:05:15.362 --> 00:05:17.329
we started off by asking students
我们从问学生

107
00:05:17.353 --> 00:05:18.507
what they liked,
他们喜欢什么，

108
00:05:18.531 --> 00:05:19.682
what they didn't like
不喜欢什么，

109
00:05:19.706 --> 00:05:21.190
and what they found confusing.
还有他们对什么感到疑惑开始。

110
00:05:21.562 --> 00:05:25.507
Eventually we began asking what they wished they could do.
最后我们问他们： 他们希望自己能干什么。

111
00:05:25.969 --> 00:05:29.389
Their feedback gave us concrete items to build in
他们的回答让我们知道 具体应该在项目中加入什么，

112
00:05:29.413 --> 00:05:33.096
to be sure that we were including student voices in what we were designing.
以保证我们在设计的项目中 融合了学生们的愿望。

113
00:05:33.850 --> 00:05:38.447
Overall, what we have learned is that this is the beginning of a new platform
总的来说，我们了解到 这是一个新平台的开始。

114
00:05:38.471 --> 00:05:41.369
for giving students both voice and ownership
它给学生们发声的机会和所有权

115
00:05:41.393 --> 00:05:43.643
in deciding how they want to have impact
在决定他们如何对自己未来的职业

116
00:05:43.667 --> 00:05:45.048
in their careers.
造成影响。

117
00:05:45.513 --> 00:05:47.073
We focused on science,
我们把精力集中在科学上，

118
00:05:47.097 --> 00:05:48.763
because we know we need scientists
因为我们知道人类需要科学家

119
00:05:48.787 --> 00:05:51.814
to help us solve our current and future challenges.
来解决现有的和未来的挑战。

120
00:05:52.357 --> 00:05:56.456
But virtual reality could support students in any area.
不过，虚拟现实可以 在各个领域帮到学生。

121
00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:01.012
How could we support students in exploring all of their desires
我们如何利用这些 令人大开眼界的经历和

122
00:06:01.036 --> 00:06:05.156
with these eye-opening experiences and chances to learn from primary sources?
从主要资源中学习的机会 来帮助学生探索他们的愿望？

123
00:06:05.180 --> 00:06:09.770
Could we create VR for inexpensive headsets
我们可以为廉价的耳机 添加 VR 功能，

124
00:06:09.794 --> 00:06:12.551
that lets them be immersed in oral literature
让学生们沉浸在口头文学中，

125
00:06:12.575 --> 00:06:14.845
or in critical moments of human history?
或者历史上的重要时刻吗？

126
00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:19.385
Extended reality has the potential to change the trajectory
扩展现实有能力改变孩子们

127
00:06:19.409 --> 00:06:20.880
of our children's lives
生活的方式，

128
00:06:20.904 --> 00:06:23.906
and lead them to careers they never imagined
通过给他们机会 看到自己能成为什么样的人，

129
00:06:23.930 --> 00:06:27.245
by giving them the chance to see what they can be.
带他们体验自己从未想象过的职业。

130
00:06:27.613 --> 00:06:28.825
Thank you.
谢谢。

131
00:06:28.849 --> 00:06:31.573
(Applause)
（鼓掌）